Peel and finely chop the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and finely chopped) and @onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Remove the stalk and the core from the @red pepper{1}(stalk and core removed) and chop it into ½cm squares. Roughly chop the @button mushrooms{1}(roughly chopped). Drain and rinse the @red kidney beans{1/2%can}. Remove the @flat leaf parsley{2}(leaves removed from stems) leaves from their stems and roughly chop them.

Heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a medium-sized #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the garlic and onion. Gently fry for ~{1%minute} or until soft. Add the red pepper and mushrooms. Gently fry for a further ~{2-3%minutes} or until soft.

> Tip: Add a splash of white wine if you have it to help add another dimension to this dish!

Boil some water in a #kettle{}. Place the @vegetable stock pot{1} into a #measuring jug{}. Add 400ml of boiling water. Stir until it's dissolved.

Add the @risotto rice{2/3%cup}, @smoked paprika{1.5%tsp} and @ground turmeric{1/2%tsp} to your pepper and onion mix in the frying pan. Stir to coat and mix the ingredients.

Pour in the stock. Add the kidney beans, half of the parsley, the @tomato puree{1}, @peas{1%cup} and @salt{1/4%tsp}. Stir to combine and dissolve the tomato puree. Reduce the heat to medium-low and cook for about ~{20%minutes}.

> Tip: Don't be tempted to stir too much - good paella always has a crusty bottom (it's what's known as the 'socarrat')!

Cover the frying pan with a #lid{} for ~{5%minutes} before the end of cooking.

> Tip: If you don't have a lid for your pan, you can use a big plate. Be careful when you take the plate off, it'll be hot!

After this time, check the liquid has all soaked up and take the paella off the heat. Leave the lid on for a further ~{5%minutes}. While you're waiting, slice the @lemon{1/2}(sliced into wedges) into wedges (you'll only really need to use half of it) and chop the @black olives{30}(chopped).

Serve by garnishing with your remaining parsley, wedges of lemon and the olives scattered over the top. Go for it!